
      <html xmlns:o='urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office' xmlns:w='urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:word' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40'>
      <head><meta charset='utf-8'><title>Lesson Note</title>
      <style>
        body { font-family: 'Times New Roman', serif; line-height: 1.5; padding: 20px; }
        h1 { text-align: center; text-transform: uppercase; border-bottom: 2px solid black; }
        h2 { text-transform: uppercase; text-decoration: underline; margin-top: 20px; font-size: 16pt; }
        .font-bold { font-weight: bold; }
        .section { margin-bottom: 15px; }
        ul, ol { margin-left: 25px; }
      </style>
      </head><body>
    <div class="mb-8 border-b-2 border-slate-900 pb-4"><h1 class="text-3xl font-black text-center mb-6 uppercase tracking-tight">Lesson Note</h1><div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-y-3 text-sm md:text-base"><p><span class="font-bold">Subject:</span> English Language</p><p><span class="font-bold">Class:</span> SSS 1</p><p><span class="font-bold">Theme / Aspect:</span> Grammar</p><p><span class="font-bold">Topic:</span> Complex sentences – structure, types of clauses, and examples</p><p><span class="font-bold">Duration:</span> 40 minutes</p><p><span class="font-bold">Date:</span> May 22nd, 2024</p><p class="md:col-span-2"><span class="font-bold">Reference Books:</span> New Oxford Secondary English Course for Senior Secondary Schools (Book 1) by Ayo Banjo et al; Intensive English for Senior Secondary Schools by Benson O. A. Oluikpe; Current English Grammar and Usage.</p><p class="md:col-span-2"><span class="font-bold">Instructional Materials:</span> A chart showing various subordinating conjunctions, Whiteboard, Markers, and Sentence flashcards.</p></div></div><section class="mb-8 section"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 uppercase underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4">Behavioural Objectives</h2><p class="mb-2">By the end of the lesson, students should be able to:</p><ul class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-1"><li>Define a complex sentence and identify its structure.</li><li>Distinguish between an independent (main) clause and a dependent (subordinate) clause.</li><li>Identify at least five subordinating conjunctions used in complex sentences.</li><li>Construct five original complex sentences using appropriate punctuation.</li></ul></section><section class="mb-8 section"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 uppercase underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4">Previous Knowledge (Entry Behaviour)</h2><p>The students have already learned about simple sentences (subject and predicate) and compound sentences using coordinating conjunctions (FANBOYS).</p></section><section class="mb-8 section"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 uppercase underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4">Introduction (Set Induction)</h2><p>The teacher introduces the lesson by writing two related ideas on the board: 'I stayed at home' and 'It was raining'. The teacher then asks the students how these two thoughts can be joined together to show that one depends on the other. This leads to the introduction of the complex sentence.</p></section><section class="mb-8 section border-2 border-slate-900 p-6 bg-slate-50 shadow-inner"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-center uppercase border-b-2 border-slate-900 pb-2">Student's Note (Board Summary)</h2><div class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-lg leading-loose">COMPLEX SENTENCES: STRUCTURE AND CLAUSES

1. DEFINITION: A complex sentence is a sentence that contains one independent (main) clause and at least one dependent (subordinate) clause. Unlike a compound sentence where both parts are equal, in a complex sentence, one part is more important than the other.

2. TYPES OF CLAUSES:
   A. Independent (Main) Clause: This is a group of words that has a subject and a verb and can stand alone as a complete thought. Example: 'The students shouted for joy.'
   B. Dependent (Subordinate) Clause: This is a group of words that has a subject and a verb but cannot stand alone because it does not express a complete thought. It starts with a subordinating conjunction. Example: '...when the principal announced the holiday.'

3. THE STRUCTURE: 
A complex sentence is formed by: Independent Clause + Subordinate Clause OR Subordinate Clause + Comma + Independent Clause.

4. SUBORDINATING CONJUNCTIONS: These are words used to join the dependent clause to the independent clause. Common examples include: because, although, if, since, while, unless, until, before, after, even though, and whenever.

5. PUNCTUATION RULES:
   - If the dependent clause comes before the independent clause, a comma is used after the dependent clause. Example: 'Because he was late, he missed the test.'
   - If the independent clause comes first, no comma is generally needed. Example: 'He missed the test because he was late.'

6. DETAILED EXAMPLES:
   - Example 1: Although the road was bumpy (Dependent), we reached the village on time (Independent).
   - Example 2: The farmer planted his seeds (Independent) after the first rain fell (Dependent).
   - Example 3: If you study hard (Dependent), you will excel in your WAEC (Independent).
   - Example 4: She did not attend the wedding (Independent) because she was ill (Dependent).</div></section><section class="mb-8 section"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 uppercase underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4">Presentation (Teaching Steps)</h2><div class="space-y-6"><div class="border-l-4 border-slate-300 pl-4 py-1"><h3 class="font-bold uppercase text-sm text-slate-600 mb-2">Step 1</h3><div class="space-y-3"><div><span class="font-bold block">Teacher’s Activity:</span><p>The teacher defines a complex sentence and explains the difference between independent and dependent clauses using real-life examples.</p></div><div><span class="font-bold block">Student’s Activity:</span><p>The students listen and write down the definitions in their notebooks.</p></div></div></div><div class="border-l-4 border-slate-300 pl-4 py-1"><h3 class="font-bold uppercase text-sm text-slate-600 mb-2">Step 2</h3><div class="space-y-3"><div><span class="font-bold block">Teacher’s Activity:</span><p>The teacher lists common subordinating conjunctions on the board and explains how they function as 'links' between the two clauses.</p></div><div><span class="font-bold block">Student’s Activity:</span><p>The students repeat the conjunctions and identify the one used in sample sentences provided on the chart.</p></div></div></div><div class="border-l-4 border-slate-300 pl-4 py-1"><h3 class="font-bold uppercase text-sm text-slate-600 mb-2">Step 3</h3><div class="space-y-3"><div><span class="font-bold block">Teacher’s Activity:</span><p>The teacher demonstrates the correct use of commas when starting a complex sentence with a subordinate clause.</p></div><div><span class="font-bold block">Student’s Activity:</span><p>The students practice placing commas in sentences written on the board.</p></div></div></div><div class="border-l-4 border-slate-300 pl-4 py-1"><h3 class="font-bold uppercase text-sm text-slate-600 mb-2">Step 4</h3><div class="space-y-3"><div><span class="font-bold block">Teacher’s Activity:</span><p>The teacher facilitates a short drill where students are given a main clause and must add a dependent clause to make it complex.</p></div><div><span class="font-bold block">Student’s Activity:</span><p>The students participate in the oral drill and provide various dependent clauses.</p></div></div></div></div></section><section class="mb-8 section"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 uppercase underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4">Evaluation</h2><ul class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2"><li>What is the difference between an independent clause and a dependent clause?</li><li>Identify the subordinating conjunction in this sentence: 'Wait here until I return'.</li><li>Rewrite the following two simple sentences as one complex sentence: 'The bell rang. The students ran to the field.'</li><li>Where should a comma be placed if a dependent clause starts a sentence?</li></ul></section><section class="mb-8 section"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 uppercase underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4">Summary / Conclusion</h2><p>In this lesson, we have explored the structure of complex sentences. We learned that a complex sentence must have one main clause and at least one subordinate clause, connected by a subordinating conjunction. We also emphasized the importance of using a comma when the subordinate clause begins the sentence.</p></section><section class="mb-4 section"><h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 uppercase underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4">Assignment (Homework)</h2><p>Underline the dependent clause in the following sentences and circle the subordinating conjunction: 1. Unless you apologize, I will not talk to you. 2. We will go for the excursion if the school provides a bus. 3. Since it is dark, we must carry a torch. 4. Whenever I see her, she is reading a book. 5. He failed the interview even though he was well-prepared.</p></section></body></html>